12 358-A:17 CoreConsumerProtections.
13 I. For first time customers, an operator shall not accept or dispense, in the aggregate, more
14 than $5,000 per customer per calendar day across all kiosks under common control within the
15 UnitedStates.
16 II. For existing customers, an operator shall not accept or dispense, in the aggregate, more
17 than $15,000 per customer per calendar day across all kiosks under common control within the
18 UnitedStates.
19 III. Before accepting funds, all kiosks shall display conspicuous warnings, including that no
20 government agency, law enforcement, court, utility, bank, tech support, employer, or retailer will
21 ever demand payment by crypto ATM. The kiosk shall require the customer to answer fraud-
22 screening prompts, including whether they are being coached by another person. If the customer
23 indicates a risk of fraud, the kiosk shall block the transaction and display law enforcement and
24 consumerprotectionandantitrustbureaucontactinformation.
25 IV. Operatorsshallusecommerciallyreasonableblockchainanalyticstoblocktransferstoor
26 from wallet addresses flagged for association with scams, theft, sanctions, or other illicit activity,
27 andshallmaintainwrittenanti-fraudandconsumerprotectionpolicies.
28 V. Before accepting funds, kiosks shall disclose in writing and on-screen all fees, the spread
29 between the operator’s price and the reference price, expressed as a percentage and dollar amount,
30 andthetotaldigitalassetexpectedtobedelivered.
31 VI. The kiosk shall provide a printed or electronic receipt summarizing the transaction,
32 including the operator's name and toll-free live customer service phone number, the kiosk's location,
33 a timestamp, the name of the asset, the quantity of the asset, the asset's reference price, the asset's
34 spread, all fees paid, the total amount paid, the wallet address or voucher ID, and any applicable
35 cancellationcodes.
